00:53:55.639 --> 00:54:03.959
open AI and Google and Amazon and Microsoft on what they're rolling out on a weekly basis.

00:54:04.840 --> 00:54:06.439
And it's hard.

00:54:09.479 --> 00:54:11.800
Greg, I see you have your hand raised. Want to jump in here?

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:20.679
Yeah, absolutely. Gerard, I actually started my career as an actuary with Mercer,

00:54:20.679 --> 00:54:24.760
now work for Charles Schwab. I was just wondering, I'm out of the actuarial space,

00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:31.320
but I still remember those days and that was definitely the rise of open source. I was

00:54:31.320 --> 00:54:37.719
wondering if you use any open source packages for any of the actuarial side work that you might do?

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:50.360
I don't know. I don't know with a hundred percent certainty. I would find it almost impossible to

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:58.280
believe that there's no open source being used. But I wouldn't be surprised if it is the core

00:54:58.280 --> 00:55:07.879
of our top product that someone took it completely apart and rewrote it completely from the first

00:55:07.879 --> 00:55:12.280
letter to the last letter of that open package. I wouldn't be surprised.

00:55:13.560 --> 00:55:17.239
Yeah, absolutely. It seems like there's lots of opportunity there, Matt, so I appreciate that.

00:55:21.159 --> 00:55:27.560
I see Jacob had a question that was, Gerard, do your actuaries and data scientists collaborate

00:55:27.560 --> 00:55:31.239
on projects at Prudential? And if so, how does that usually work?

00:55:32.679 --> 00:55:40.760
I would imagine. I'm not really involved in that space because only when they create something

00:55:40.760 --> 00:55:47.239
that needs to be moved to production, the operational risk team really gets involved and

00:55:47.239 --> 00:55:55.239
we get to know what they're doing. I hope at one point I'll see something like that come by.

00:55:56.040 --> 00:56:01.719
Also, I've only been with Prudential for like a year and a half, so I have not nearly scratched

00:56:01.719 --> 00:56:07.879
the surface of what happens within all the nooks and crannies of the company.

00:56:08.520 --> 00:56:16.360
Yeah, definitely. Well, I know as we get to the end here, I always love to ask this question,

00:56:16.360 --> 00:56:21.479
so I want to make sure to squeeze it in. But what is one of the most memorable pieces of

00:56:21.479 --> 00:56:26.520
career advice that you've either received or given throughout your professional journey?

00:56:30.520 --> 00:56:38.520
I thought about it after we did our prep meeting. Let me rephrase it as the most impactful

00:56:39.639 --> 00:56:44.679
that happened to me. I was born and raised in the Netherlands. I worked for a little company

00:56:45.239 --> 00:56:54.280
at the time, and my mentor at the time emigrated to Curacao, which is in the Caribbean.

00:56:57.239 --> 00:57:01.560
I was trying to make a career switch, and I asked him for advice. He said,

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:09.639
why don't you come work with me? Four weeks later, I was on a Caribbean island working there.

00:57:09.639 --> 00:57:14.199
So that was the most impactful advice that I ever followed, but I'm not so sure if it's

00:57:14.199 --> 00:57:20.360
applicable to a lot of people on the call right now. Hey, it's impactful to you.

00:57:22.760 --> 00:57:27.479
Well, thank you all so much for joining us. Thank you so much, Gerard. I really appreciate it.

00:57:28.199 --> 00:57:29.560
Sure. Thanks. It was a blast.

